[1] Mexico (Jalisco)
Date: Fri 4 Jun 2010
Source: El Informador [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.informador.com.mx/jalisco/2010/206824/6/casos-de-dengue-se-cuadruplican-en-comparacion-con-el-ano-pasado.htm>


[Dengue] cases quadrupled in comparison with last year [2009]. The
state's challenge was to end this year [2010] without deaths caused
by this disease.

The dengue outbreak continues actively in Jalisco since the end of
2009, but this is not to say that the actions taken do not have
impact, stated the Secretary of Health of Jalisco, Alfonso Petersen
Farah. As for deaths, there is a reduced trend but an increase among
the number of infected individuals. The increase is considerable; up
to epidemiological week [EW] 20 of 2009, which included 17-23 May
2009, the health agency confirmed 131 cases, 11 of these DHF.
However, in the same [EW] of 2010, there are 502 infected
individuals, 77 of which have the most severe type of the disease
[DHF]. This signifies that there are 4 times more infected
individuals than in 2009.

Petersen Farah warns that the increase in infected people is due to
the strengthened epidemiological surveillance system, with the
reporting of more cases. According to the Center for Epidemiological
Surveillance and Disease Control (CENAVECE), of the federal
Secretariat of Health, there are more than 2000 probable [dengue]
cases in the state. That is to say that 2000 persons presented with
symptoms related to the virus [infection] but were not confirmed by
laboratory tests.

Last year [2009], the federal Secretariat of Health closed [the year]
with almost 60 000 probable cases of the [dengue] virus [infection],
with 5000 confirmed in Jalisco.

However, to have a continuous outbreak during the 1st half of the
year [2010] with [only] one recorded death indicates that the trend
is not so negative as one might think. For 4 months of the year and
with an active outbreak, to have one death leads us to a trend
infinitely less than that of the past year [2009]; however, we do not
cease to be worried.

Despite the actions against the virus, the state's challenge was to
finish the [current] year with zero deaths.

--
