[4] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Th 17 Jun 2010
Source: Terra [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/noticias/0,,OI4501632-EI306,00-Com+casos+de+dengue+ate+no+frio+RJ+deve+ter+epidemia+em.html>


The state of Rio [de Janeiro] may have a dengue epidemic next summer,
fear [health] authorities, who are running against time to reduce the
number of _Aedes aegypti_ breeding sites and the return of [dengue]
virus type 1, which this year [2010] was isolated in Rio [de Janeiro
city], and in Paraty, Angra dos Reis, Campos and Natividade.

This [dengue] virus [serotype], which caused an epidemic in 1986, has
not circulated since the beginning of the 1990s decade. Because of
this, all those who were born after this period do not have any
immunity against it. Since January 2010, the reintroduction of dengue
[virus] types 1 and 2 now cause epidemics in 20 of the 92
municipalities in the state with 21 confirmed deaths.

"We are working based on the worst scenario, which was the epidemic
of 2008 caused by [dengue] virus type 2. But we hope this does not
happen. [Dengue virus] type 1 was identified in the metropolitan
region and, because of this, we intensified preventive work to avoid
the occurrence of an epidemic in the state. This possibility worries
us because the number of people susceptible to this virus type is
very large, now that we have past nearly 20 years without it
circulating," said the Superintendent of Environmental and
Epidemiological Surveillance of the state Secretariat of Health and
Civil Defense, Alexandre Chieppe, who is in Brazilia discussing
strategies against dengue.

The dengue vector mosquito normally reproduces when it is hot. But,
despite cold weather, cities such as Campos, Macae, Angra dos Reis
and Cabo Frio have recorded a significant increase in illnesses in
April and May 2010, a period when generally a decline is registered.
"This year [2010], the epidemic curve has changed in some
municipalities. The dengue cases have extended into colder months.
Possibly, this occurred due to the reentry of dengue [virus] type 1.
This is an association, but we have not reached a conclusion," said Chieppe.

The Coordinator of Epidemiological Surveillance of the state, Rita
Vassoler, said on Monday [14 Jun 2010] that 20 municipalities in Rio
de Janeiro are facing a dengue epidemic. "In these localities, the
incidence is greater than 300 cases per 100 000 population." In
Itaperuna, for example, the index in 2010, according to the state, is
1168 per 100 000 population. The city registered 388 cases of dengue
in April and 605 in May [2010]. Last year [2009], there were 11 cases
in April and 15 in May [2009]. Chieppe, however, stated that Rio does
not face an epidemic scenario. "These cities had epidemics, but today
the number of cases is falling," he said.

Rio has 2 characteristics that, according to specialists, are
worrying: people who are susceptible to the virus and a large
quantity of mosquito vectors. In the state, 55 percent of the
municipalities are in an alert situation for outbreaks and epidemics,
according to the latest household infestation rates released in March 2010.

"We have until November to maximally reduce the numbers of mosquito
breeding foci. We are intensifying out work. The prospects were to
have more than 2000 fire fighters to help municipal officials," said
Chieppe. "Today, there are 3000. For the 1st time, the dengue
situation room, an interdisciplinary group against the disease,
continued [to function] after summer ended. The population needs to
collaborate, since the majority of the [mosquito] breeding sites are
within residences."

In February [2010], the Ministry of Health had alerted the states in
the country to be attentive to the possibility of the reintroduction
of [dengue virus] type 1. Children and adolescents born after the
decade of the 90s could be the majority [of cases].

