[6] Brazil (Alagoas)
Date: Thu 17 Jun 2010
Source: Alagoas 24 Horas [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY]
<http://www.alagoas24horas.com.br/conteudo/?vCod=87303>


Worried by the dengue advance in Alagoas, the representatives of the
Committee for Mobilization Against Dengue met in the morning this
Wednesday 16 [Jun 2010] with various community leaders to plot
strategies to curb the number of cases. The objective, according to
the Director of Health Promotion, Fatima Lima, is to discuss the
situation with community leaders and institutional representatives
beyond their own communities to train multiplier agents [health
agents who train other agents].

According to the numbers presented by Lima, the number of registered
dengue cases up to the present is 26 000. Some await confirmation.
However, if compared to the same period last year [2009], the number
is frightening, because in 2009, there were nearly 3000.

According to the spokesperson of the state Secretariat of Health,
they are already taking action to combat the proliferation of the
dengue mosquito, in addition to assessing strategies. The increase in
the number of cases in 2010 was more than 900 percent compared to
last year [2009].

The simplest way to prevent dengue is to avoid reproduction of the
mosquito _Aedes aegypti_, because just one mosquito can infect 300
people [Although not every dengue virus-infected mosquito infects
nearly this many people, one or 2 is enough to keep the virus
circulating. - Mod.TY]. Because of this, it is necessary to eliminate
the places that they seek for reproduction; it is imperative to not
let clean water accumulate in any type of container.

--
