[7] Argentina
Date: Fri 4 Jun 2010
Source: Ministerio de Salud de la Nacion [in Spanish, trans. & summ.
Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.msal.gov.ar/archivos/Dengue%20parte%20de%20prensa%2030-05-2010.pdf>


From December 2009 to present [30 May 2010], the circulation of
dengue [viruses] type 1 [DENV-1], 2 [DENV-2] and 4 [DENV-4] have been
confirmed in Argentina. From 1 Jan 2010 to date, there have been 1185
illnesses compatible with dengue.

The following provides details for the dengue situation in each
province of residence for the dengue-compatible cases:

Buenos Aires city: 5 cases, none confirmed, continued under investigation.

Buenos Aires province: 25 cases, 4 confirmed, 3 with DENV-1, all with
travel histories outside the province, one case with DENV-2 without
outside travel history. The remaining 21 ill individuals are not yet
confirmed and are distributed in 15 localities.

Catamarca: one case of DENV-1 with travel history to an affected area.

Chaco: outbreak in Corzuela since February 2010 with circulation of
DENV-1; 93 illnesses

Chubut: one unconfirmed with travel history to an affected area

Corrientes: 2 dengue cases with travel history to an affected area, 9
[acquired locally] in 2 locations.

Entre Rios: 3 with travel history to an affected area (one to Brazil,
2 in Argentina)

Formosa: one with travel history to Paraguay

Jujuy: DENV-1 confirmed in 2 people, 4 suspected; all locally acquired.

La Pampa: 2 suspected with travel history to affected areas

Mendoza: one confirmed case with travel history to Bolivia

Misiones: dengue outbreak since December 2009; 872 illnesses in 2010;
753 confirmed, 119 under investigation

Salta: 59 DENV-2 cases, confirmed in 3; all with travel history to
affected areas.

Santa Fe: 20 cases, 8 confirmed; DENV-1, DENV-2 and DENV-4 identified
in residents of Rosario, with one DENV-4 locally acquired; 5 cases
under investigation.

Santiago de Estero: 70 reported dengue cases; DENV-1 outbreak confirmed.

Activities continue in outbreak areas; assistance services have been
strengthened for control actions by provincial and national technical
and health teams. Control actions include trash cleanup, destruction
of mosquito breeding sites and application of larvicides, fumigation
of blocks adjacent to homes of infected people, spatial mapping and
search for febrile patients with dengue symptoms.

--
